"adj. (伤)青灰色的；(脸色)苍白的)；狂怒的 【英】 adj. 青灰色的(撞伤)；(脸 色)苍白的(white; pale) 【例】 a face livid with cold adj. (由于瘀伤而)青灰色的; (脸色)苍白的 【记】由于太vivid(adj 活泼的), 所以livid. 【记】livered 肝的颜色(只是助记)，动了肝火气得肝都变色了 【相关】vivid 活泼的，生动的, 鲜明的, 鲜艳的, 大胆的 livid (adj.)  early 15c., ""of a bluish-leaden color,"" from Middle French livide and directly from Latin lividus ""of a bluish color, black and blue,"" figuratively ""envious, spiteful, malicious,"" from livere ""be bluish,"" earlier *slivere, from PIE *sliwo-, suffixed form of root *(s)leie- ""bluish"" (cognates: Old Church Slavonic and Russian sliva ""plum;"" Lithuanian slywas ""plum;"" Old Irish li, Welsh lliw ""color, splendor,"" Old English sla ""sloe""). The sense of ""furiously angry"" (1912) is from the notion of being livid with rage."
